# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blockchain-oracles
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blockchain-oracles/blockchain-oracle] A **blockchain oracle** is a third-party service for smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/blockchain-oracle] Oracles provide trusted information based on the outside-world sources to the on-blockchain smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/blockchain-oracle] An oracle typically encapsulates the real-world complexity outside of the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/blockchain-oracle] This provides different engineering advantages, chiefly that critical errors and potential points of failure are easier to mitigate off-chain than on-chain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/blockchain-oracle] For example, in a contract to automatically purchase bitcoins at a predetermined price, the fulfillment condition is based on the current exchange rate for the bitcoin; an off-chain oracle can constantly monitor the price to provide the triggering condition to the contract.
[src:blockchain-oracles/blockchain-oracle] If an oracle relies on a single source of truth (*centralized*), that can lead to issues: the data source can be hacked in a man-in-the-middle attack, or altered by its owner, in order to sway smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/blockchain-oracle] *Decentralized* oracles (*consensus oracles*) increase the reliability of the information provided to smart contracts by querying multiple data sources, thus distributing trust between participants.
[src:blockchain-oracles/blockchain-oracle] However, this does not achieve trustlessness, since oracles are not part of the main blockchain consensus, and thus not part of the security mechanisms of public blockchains.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] Chainlink was created in 2017 by Sergey Nazarov and Steve Ellis, who co-authored a white paper introducing the Chainlink protocol and network with Cornell University professor Ari Juels the same year.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] Chainlink acts as a "bridge" between a blockchain and off-chain environments.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] The network, which services smart contracts, was formally launched in 2019.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] In 2018, Chainlink integrated Town Crier, a trusted execution environment-based blockchain oracle that Juels also worked on.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] Town Crier connects the Ethereum blockchain with web sources that use HTTPS.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] In 2020, Chainlink integrated DECO, a Cornell project co-created by Juels.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] DECO is described by its authors as a protocol that uses zero-knowledge proofs to allow users to prove information is true to a blockchain oracle without revealing sensitive information, such as birth dates.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] In 2020, Chainlink launched a proof-of-reserve (PoR) system intended to help cryptocurrency projects and tokenized-asset issuers verify asset backing.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] In 2022, Chainlink announced and launched BUILD, a program under Chainlink Economics 2.0 for projects that commit a portion of their fees and incentives to support the Chainlink ecosystem.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] In 2023, Chainlink introduced the Cross-Chain Interoperability Protocol (CCIP), designed to enable communication between applications across blockchains and traditional financial systems.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] In August 2023, SWIFT reported results from experiments using CCIP with SWIFT messaging to transfer tokenized assets across multiple public and private blockchains.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] In November 2024, a SWIFT, UBS Asset Management, Chainlink working under the Monetary Authority of Singapore demonstrated settlement of tokenized fund subscriptions and redemptions over the SWIFT network using Chainlink.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] In 2025, the United States Department of Commerce used Chainlink to publish U.S. government macroeconomic data on blockchains.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] Morgan's Kinexys, and Ondo Finance executed a cross-chain Delivery vs.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] Payment (DvP) transaction using the Chainlink Runtime Environment.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] On October 31, 2025, the Hong Kong Monetary Authority and the Central Bank of Brazil carried out a cross-border trade finance pilot using CBDCs and smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] The test connected Brazil's Drex wholesale CBDC system with HKMA's Ensemble platform through Chainlink.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] Chainlink's oracle network allows blockchains to connect to off-chain data and computation resources.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] LINK is a utility and governance token of Chainlink.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] The trade value derived from these tokens is used to pay node operators for retrieving data from smart contracts, and also for deposits placed by node operators as required by contract creators.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] Tokens can be stored in any ERC-20 wallet, as the ERC677 token retains all the functionality of an ERC-20 token.
[src:blockchain-oracles/chainlink-blockchain-oracle] Community participants can stake LINK to support the network's cryptoeconomic security.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] A core principle of DeFi is its accessibility.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] By operating on public blockchains, DeFi applications (commonly referred to as "dApps") enable users from across the globe to access financial services without the need for a centralized authority or compliance with traditional Know Your Customer (KYC) and Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] DeFi also introduces programmability and composability to finance.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Developers can create interoperable financial products by combining different DeFi protocols like building blocks, a concept often referred to as "money Legos".
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Decentralized exchanges (abbreviated DEXs) are alternative payment ecosystems that use new protocols for financial transactions.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] They emerged within decentralized finance (DeFi), a sector of blockchain technology and fintech.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Centralized exchanges (CEXs), DEXs and DEX aggregators are all built on a multi-layered DeFi architecture, with each layer serving a well-defined purpose.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] (See Figure: *Multi-layered Architecture of the DeFi Stack*).
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] While they share common components of the first four layers, such as *the Settlement layer*, *Asset layer*, *Protocol layer* and *Application layer*, DEX aggregators have an additional component or *Aggregator layer*, which allows them to connect and interact with other DEXs via smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] The Ethereum blockchain popularized smart contracts, which are the basis of DeFi, in 2017.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Other blockchains have since implemented smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Alternative Layer 1 protocols, such as Radix, have been developed utilizing sharded consensus mechanisms to attempt to resolve scalability issues inherent in earlier blockchains.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] As of 2021, MakerDAO was a prominent lending DeFi platform based on a stablecoin that was established in 2017.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] It allowed users to borrow DAI, a token pegged to the US dollar.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Through a set of smart contracts that govern the loan, repayment, and liquidation processes, MakerDAO aimed to maintain the stable value of DAI in a decentralized and autonomous manner.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] In September 2024, MakerDAO rebranded as Sky, and its stablecoin DAI was renamed USDS.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] As of March 2025, the combined circulating supply of DAI and USDS stood at approximately US$9 billion.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] In June 2020, Compound Finance, a decentralized finance protocol enabling users to lend or borrow cryptocurrency assets and which provides typical interest payments to lenders, started rewarding lenders and borrowers with a cryptocurrency called Comp.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] This token, which is used for running Compound, can also be traded on cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] In July 2020, *The Washington Post* described decentralized finance techniques and the risks involved.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] In September 2020, Bloomberg said that DeFi made up two-thirds of the cryptocurrency market in terms of price changes and that DeFi collateral levels had reached $9 billion.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Ethereum saw a rise in developers during 2020 due to the increased interest in DeFi.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Total collateral levels across DeFi protocols reached a peak of $178 billion in November 2021, before declining to under $40 billion by 2023 amid broader downturns in the cryptocurrency market.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] DeFi has attracted venture capitalists such as Andreessen Horowitz and Michael Novogratz.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] The evolution of Decentralized Finance (DeFi) began with Bitcoin in 2009 and matured with Ethereum’s 2015 launch, which introduced smart contracts and enabled decentralized applications.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] By 2021, DeFi protocols such as MakerDAO, Compound, Aave, and Uniswap had driven total value locked (TVL) to over $180 billion.The 2022 crypto market crash, which followed events like the collapse of Terra/LUNA and FTX, exposed critical vulnerabilities in the DeFi space and triggered a downturn.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] A key trend was the tokenization of real-world assets (RWA) such as treasury bills, real estate, and carbon credits.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Platforms like MakerDAO and Centrifuge enabled institutional investors to access on-chain yield tied to off-chain assets.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Layer 2 scaling solutions such as Arbitrum and Optimism also gained traction, reducing transaction fees and increasing throughput on top of Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] This period also marked the rise of intent-based DeFi, allowing users to specify desired outcomes, with protocols handling transaction logic (Bankless, 2023).
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] In 2024, regulatory developments shaped DeFi's evolution.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] The European Union’s MiCA framework (Markets in Crypto-Assets Regulation) came into effect, impacting stablecoin issuers and custodial services.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] In response, many DeFi projects began adopting hybrid models, combining decentralized architecture with off-chain compliance layers to navigate legal requirements.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Meanwhile, interoperability improved with the deployment of cross-chain bridges like Wormhole V2 and Chainlink CCIP, enabling liquidity to flow between Ethereum, Solana, Avalanche, and other ecosystems.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] DeFi revolves around decentralized applications, also known as DApps, that perform financial functions on distributed ledgers called blockchains, a technology that was made popular by Bitcoin and has since been adapted more broadly.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Rather than transactions being made through a centralized intermediary such as a cryptocurrency exchange or a traditional securities exchange, transactions are directly made between participants, mediated by smart contract programs.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] These smart contracts, or DeFi protocols, typically run using open-source software that is built and maintained by a community of developers.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] DApps are typically accessed through a browser extension or application.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] For example, MetaMask allows users to directly interact with Ethereum through a digital wallet.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Many of these DApps can be linked to create complex financial services.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Examples include lending protocols, in which stablecoin holders can lend assets such as USD Coin or DAI to a liquidity pool in a borrow/lending protocol such as the Aave protocol, and allow others to borrow those digital assets by depositing their own collateral.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] The protocol automatically adjusts interest rates based on the demand for the asset.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Some DApps source external (off-chain) data, such as the price of an asset, through blockchain oracles.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Aave Protocol popularized "flash loans", which are uncollateralized loans of an arbitrary amount that are taken out and paid back within a single blockchain transaction.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Max Wolff is credited with the original invention of flash loans with the original implementation released in 2018 by Marble Protocol.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Many exploits of DeFi platforms have used flash loans to manipulate cryptocurrency spot prices.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Another DeFi protocol is Uniswap, which is a decentralized exchange (DEX) set up to trade tokens issued on Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Rather than using a centralized exchange to fill orders, Uniswap pays users to form liquidity pools in exchange for a percentage of the fees collected from traders swapping tokens in and out of the liquidity pools.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Because no centralized party runs Uniswap (the platform is governed by its users), and any development team can use the open-source software, there is no entity to check the identities of the people using the platform and meet KYC/AML regulations.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] As of 2020, it was not clear what position regulators would take on the legality of such platforms; subsequent regulatory developments are summarised in the Regulation section.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Decentralized exchanges (DEX) are a type of cryptocurrency exchange, which allow for either direct peer-to-peer, or Automated Market Maker (AMM) liquidity pool cryptocurrency transactions to take place without the need for an intermediary.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] The lack of an intermediary differentiates them from centralized exchanges (CEX).
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] In transactions made through decentralized exchanges, the typical third party entities which would normally oversee the security and transfer of assets (e.g. banks, stockbrokers, online payment gateways, government institutions, etc.) are substituted by a blockchain or distributed ledger.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Some common methods of operation include the use of smart contracts or order book relaying –although numerous other variations are possible, with differing degrees of decentralization.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Because traders on a decentralized exchange often do not need to transfer their assets to the exchange before executing a trade, decentralized exchanges reduce the risk of theft from hacking of exchanges, but liquidity providers do need to transfer tokens to the decentralized exchange.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Decentralized exchanges are also more anonymous than exchanges that implement know your customer (KYC) requirements.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] As of 2018, there were signs that decentralized exchanges had been suffering from low trading volumes and reduced market liquidity.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] The 0x project, a protocol for building decentralized exchanges with interchangeable liquidity, attempted to solve this issue.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] As of mid‑2025, weekly trading volume on decentralized exchanges (DEXs) averaged around $18.6 billion, with more than 9.7 million unique wallets interacting with DeFi protocols.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Due to a lack of KYC processes, and no way to revert a transaction, users are at a loss if they are ever hacked for their passwords or private keys.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Liquidity providers staking in DeFi protocols may also suffer an impermanent loss when the relative value of the deposited token pair has shifted by the time the deposit is withdrawn.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Although liquidity pool DEX are the most widely used, they may have some drawbacks.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] The most common problems of liquidity pool DEXes are market price impact, slippage, and front running.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Price impact arises from the design of automated market makers: the larger the trade, the greater its effect on the pool's prevailing price.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] For example, if the constant product AMM is in use, every deal must keep the product xy = k constant, where x and y are quantities of two cryptocurrencies (or tokens) in the pool.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Price impact is non-linear, so the larger is the input amount Δx, the lower is the final ratio y / x that gives an exchange price.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] The problem is mostly significant for relatively large deals versus the liquidity pool size.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Front running is a special type of attack in public blockchains when some participant (usually a miner) seeing an upcoming trading transaction puts his own transaction ahead (playing with a transaction fee for example), making the initial transaction less profitable or even reverted.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] To provide some protection against front running attacks, many DeFi exchanges offer a slippage tolerance option for end-users.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] This setting allows users to set a limit on the worst acceptable execution price relative to the price observed at the time of transaction signing; if the executed price would breach that limit, the transaction reverts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Decentralized exchanges are particularly exposed to cyberattacks, and DEX-related incidents account for a major share of crypto-exchange losses.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] In 2025, at least 20 incidents were reported, resulting in aggregate losses of $535 million.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Decentralized Finance protocols exhibit varying degrees of decentralization, which largely depend on the architecture of their underlying smart contracts and external dependencies.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] When the protocol's smart contracts are deployed statically, such that the protocol's logic cannot be altered and no access-restricted functions are present, they may potentially function as neutral infrastructure.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Conversely, if the smart contracts are upgradeable or permit the modification of key parameters, or if key functions are restricted to a specific set of users, this neutrality can be compromised.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] A decentralized exchange can still have centralized components, whereby some control of the exchange is still in the hands of a central authority.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] The governance of a DeFi platform, typically as part of a Decentralized Autonomous Organization, is done through tokens that grant voting rights and are distributed amongst participants.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] However, the majority of these tokens are often held by few individuals and are rarely used to vote.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] In July 2018, the decentralized exchange Bancor was reportedly hacked and suffered a loss of $23.5 million in assets before freezing funds.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] In a Twitter tweet, Charlie Lee, the creator of Litecoin, spoke out and claimed an exchange cannot be decentralized if it can lose or freeze customer funds.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Operators of decentralized exchanges can face legal consequences from government regulators.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] One example is the founder of EtherDelta, who in November 2018 settled charges with the U.S.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Securities and Exchange Commission over operating an unregistered securities exchange.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Coding errors and hacks are common in DeFi.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Blockchain transactions are irreversible, which means that an incorrect or fraudulent DeFi transaction cannot be corrected easily if at all.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] The person or entity behind a DeFi protocol may be unknown and may disappear with investors' money.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Investor Michael Novogratz has described some DeFi protocols as "Ponzi-like".
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] DeFi has been compared to the initial coin offering craze of 2017, part of a cryptocurrency bubble.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Inexperienced investors are at particular risk of losing money because of the sophistication required to interact with DeFi platforms and the lack of any intermediary with customer support.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] On the other hand, as the code for DeFi smart contracts is generally open-source software that can be copied to set up competing platforms, experienced users and user-created bots might create instabilities as funds shift between platforms which share the same code.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] In addition, DeFi platforms might inadvertently provide incentives for cryptocurrency miners to destabilize the system.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Illicit actors, including cyber criminals, fraudsters and terrorist organisations, are exploiting the technical complexity of DeFi and the absence of AML/CFT checks to launder criminal proceeds or raise funds and crypto-assets to finance criminal activity.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] They use DeFi to obscure the movement of funds through various techniques and services.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] In 2021, half of cryptocurrency crime was related to DeFi.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] This rise has been attributed to a combination of developer incompetence and non-existent or poorly enforced regulations.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] Theft from DeFi can come from either external hackers stealing from vulnerable projects, or "rug pulls", where the developers and influencers promote a project and then take the money, as a form of pump-and-dump.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] In October 2021, the FATF included DeFi in the guidance for crypto service providers, making the authority's aim to regulate this type of asset.
[src:blockchain-oracles/decentralized-finance] They are expecting each individual country to determine if individuals involved in DeFi can be considered a virtual asset provider and be subjected to the FATF's guidelines.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Oracles are applications that produce data feeds that make offchain data sources available to the blockchain for smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This is necessary because Ethereum-based smart contracts cannot, by default, access information stored outside the blockchain network.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Giving smart contracts the ability to execute using offchain data extends the utility and value of decentralized applications.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] For instance, onchain prediction markets rely on oracles to provide information about outcomes that they use to validate user predictions.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Suppose Alice bets 20 ETH on who will become the next U.S.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] In that case, the prediction-market dapp needs an oracle to confirm election results and determine if Alice is eligible for a payout.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This page assumes the reader is familiar with Ethereum fundamentals, including nodes, consensus mechanisms, and the EVM.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] You should also have a good grasp of smart contracts and smart contract anatomy, especially .
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Oracles are applications that source, verify, and transmit external information (i.e., information stored offchain) to smart contracts running on the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Besides “pulling” offchain data and broadcasting it on Ethereum, oracles can also “push” information from the blockchain to external systems, e.g., unlocking a smart lock once the user sends a fee via an Ethereum transaction.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Without an oracle, a smart contract would be limited entirely to onchain data.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Oracles differ based on the source of data (one or multiple sources), trust models (centralized or decentralized), and system architecture (immediate-read, publish-subscribe, and request-response).
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] We can also distinguish between oracles based on whether they retrieve external data for use by onchain contracts (input oracles), send information from the blockchain to the offchain applications (output oracles), or perform computational tasks offchain (computational oracles).
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Many developers see smart contracts as code running at specific addresses on the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] But using smart contracts to enforce agreements between people isn't straightforward, given that Ethereum is deterministic.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] A deterministic system (opens in a new tab) is one that always produces the same results given an initial state and a particular input, meaning there is no randomness or variation in the process of computing outputs from inputs.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] To achieve deterministic execution, blockchains limit nodes to reaching consensus on simple binary (true/false) questions using *only* data stored on the blockchain itself.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] If blockchains received information from external sources (i.e., from the real world), determinism would be impossible to achieve, preventing nodes from agreeing on the validity of changes to the blockchain’s state.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Take for example a smart contract that executes a transaction based on the current ETH-USD exchange rate obtained from a traditional price API.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This figure is likely to change frequently (not to mention that the API could get deprecated or hacked), meaning nodes executing the same contract code would arrive at different results.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] For a public blockchain like Ethereum, with thousands of nodes around the world processing transactions, determinism is critical.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] With no central authority serving as a source of truth, nodes need mechanisms for arriving at the same state after applying the same transactions.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] A case whereby node A executes a smart contract’s code and gets "3" as a result, while node B gets "7" after running the same transaction would cause consensus to break down and eliminate Ethereum’s value as a decentralized computing platform.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This scenario also highlights the problem with designing blockchains to pull information from external sources.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Oracles, however, solve this problem by taking information from offchain sources and storing it on the blockchain for smart contracts to consume.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Since information stored onchain is unalterable and publicly available, Ethereum nodes can safely use the oracle imported offchain data to compute state changes without breaking consensus.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] To do this, an oracle is typically made up of a smart contract running onchain and some offchain components.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] The onchain contract receives requests for data from other smart contracts, which it passes to the offchain component (called an oracle node).
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This oracle node can query data sources—using application programming interfaces (APIs), for example—and send transactions to store the requested data in the smart contract's storage.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Essentially, a blockchain oracle bridges the information gap between the blockchain and the external environment, creating “hybrid smart contracts”.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] A hybrid smart contract is one that functions based on a combination of onchain contract code and offchain infrastructure.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Decentralized prediction markets are an excellent example of hybrid smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Other examples might include crop insurance smart contracts that pay out when a set of oracles determine that certain weather phenomena have taken place.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] The so-called “oracle problem” demonstrates the issues that come with using blockchain oracles to send inputs to smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Data from an oracle must be correct for a smart contract to execute correctly.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Further, having to ‘trust’ oracle operators to provide accurate information undermines the 'trustless' aspect of smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Different oracles offer different solutions to the oracle problem, which we explore later.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] **Availability**: An oracle should not delay or prevent smart contracts from executing actions and triggering state changes.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This means that data from an oracle must be *available on request* without interruption.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] **Incentive compatibility**: An oracle should incentivize offchain data providers to submit correct information to smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Incentive compatibility involves *attributability* and *accountability*.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Attributability allows for linking a piece of external information to its provider, while accountability bonds data providers to the information they give, so they can be rewarded or penalized based on the quality of information provided.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Users are entities (i.e., smart contracts) that need information external to the blockchain to complete specific actions.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] The basic workflow of an oracle service starts with the user sending a data request to the oracle contract.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] How do reporters process information from data sources and extract useful data points?
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] How many oracle nodes can participate in retrieving the data?
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] How should discrepancies in oracle reports be managed?
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] What method should be implemented in filtering submissions and aggregating reports into a single value?
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] The oracle contract is the onchain component for the oracle service.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] It listens for data requests from other contracts, relays data queries to oracle nodes, and broadcasts returned data to client contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This contract may also perform some computation on the returned data points to produce an aggregate value to send to the requesting contract.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] The oracle contract exposes some functions which client contracts call when making a data request.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Upon receiving a new query, the smart contract will emit a log event with details of the data request.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This notifies offchain nodes subscribed to the log (usually using something like the JSON-RPC `eth_subscribe` command), who proceed to retrieve data defined in the log event.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Below is an example oracle contract (opens in a new tab) by Pedro Costa.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] The oracle node is the offchain component of the oracle service.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] It extracts information from external sources, such as APIs hosted on third-party servers, and puts it onchain for consumption by smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Oracle nodes listen for events from the onchain oracle contract and proceed to complete the task described in the log.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] A common task for oracle nodes is sending a HTTP GET (opens in a new tab) request to an API service, parsing the response to extract relevant data, formatting into a blockchain-readable output, and sending it onchain by including it in a transaction to the oracle contract.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] The oracle node may also be required to attest to the validity and integrity of submitted information using “authenticity proofs”, which we explore later.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Computational oracles also rely on offchain nodes to perform computational tasks that would be impractical to execute onchain, given gas costs and block size limits.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] For example, the oracle node may be tasked with generating a verifiably random figure (e.g., for blockchain-based games).
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Oracles come in different types, including *immediate-read*, *publish-subscribe*, and *request-response*, with the latter two being the most popular among Ethereum smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Here we briefly describe the publish-subscribe and request-response models.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This type of oracle exposes a “data feed” which other contracts can regularly read for information.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] The data in this case is expected to change frequently, so client contracts must listen for updates to the data in the oracle’s storage.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] An example is an oracle that provides the latest ETH-USD price information to users.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] A request-response setup allows the client contract to request arbitrary data other than that provided by a publish-subscribe oracle.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Request-response oracles are ideal when the dataset is too large to be stored in a smart contract’s storage, and/or users will only need a small part of the data at any point in time.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Although more complex than publish-subscribe models, request-response oracles are basically what we described in the previous section.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] The oracle will have an onchain component that receives a data request and passes it to an offchain node for processing.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Users initiating data queries must cover the cost of retrieving information from the offchain source.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] The client contract must also provide funds to cover gas costs incurred by the oracle contract in returning the response via the callback function specified in the request.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] A centralized oracle is controlled by a single entity responsible for aggregating offchain information and updating the oracle contract's data as requested.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Centralized oracles are efficient since they rely on a single source of truth.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] They may function better in cases where proprietary datasets are published directly by the owner with a widely accepted signature.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] With centralized oracles, there's no way to confirm if the information provided is correct or not.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Even "reputable" providers can go rogue or get hacked.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] If the oracle becomes corrupt, smart contracts will execute based on bad data.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Centralized oracles aren't guaranteed to always make offchain data available to other smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] If the provider decides to turn off the service or a hacker hijacks the oracle's offchain component, your smart contract is at risk of a denial of service (DoS) attack.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Centralized oracles often have poorly designed or non-existent incentives for the data provider to send accurate/unaltered information.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Paying an oracle for correctness does not guarantee honesty.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This problem gets bigger as the amount of value controlled by smart contracts increases.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Decentralized oracles are designed to overcome the limitations of centralized oracles by eliminating single points of failure.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] A decentralized oracle service comprises multiple participants in a peer-to-peer network that form consensus on offchain data before sending it to a smart contract.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] A decentralized oracle should (ideally) be permissionless, trustless, and free from administration by a central party; in reality, decentralization among oracles is on a spectrum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] There are semi-decentralized oracle networks where anyone can participate, but with an “owner” that approves and removes nodes based on historical performance.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Fully decentralized oracle networks also exist: these usually run as standalone blockchains and have defined consensus mechanisms for coordinating nodes and punishing misbehavior.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Decentralized oracles attempt to achieve correctness of data using different approaches.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This includes using proofs attesting to the authenticity and integrity of the returned information and requiring multiple entities to collectively agree on the validity of offchain data.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Authenticity proofs are cryptographic mechanisms that enable independent verification of information retrieved from external sources.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] These proofs can validate the source of the information and detect possible alterations to the data after retrieval.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Certain classes of decentralized oracles require oracle node operators to provide TEE attestations.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This confirms to a user that the node operator is running an instance of oracle client in a trusted execution environment.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] TEEs prevent external processes from altering or reading an application’s code and data, hence, those attestations prove that the oracle node has kept the information intact and confidential.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Centralized oracles rely on a single source of truth when providing data to smart contracts, which introduces the possibility of publishing inaccurate information.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Decentralized oracles solve this problem by relying on multiple oracle nodes to query offchain information.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] By comparing data from multiple sources, decentralized oracles reduce the risk of passing invalid information to onchain contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Decentralized oracles, however, must deal with discrepancies in information retrieved from multiple offchain sources.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Some decentralized oracle networks require participants to vote or stake on the accuracy of answers to data queries (e.g., "Who won the 2020 US election?") using the network’s native token.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] An aggregation protocol then aggregates the votes and stakes and takes the answer supported by the majority as the valid one.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Nodes whose answers deviate from the majority answer are penalized by having their tokens distributed to others who provide more correct values.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Forcing nodes to provide a bond before providing data incentivizes honest responses since they are assumed to be rational economic actors intent on maximizing returns.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Staking/voting also protects decentralized oracles from where malicious actors create multiple identities to game the consensus system.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] However, staking cannot prevent “freeloading” (oracle nodes copying information from others) and “lazy validation” (oracle nodes following the majority without verifying the information themselves).
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Schelling point (opens in a new tab) is a game-theory concept that assumes multiple entities will always default to a common solution to a problem in absence of any communication.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Schelling-point mechanisms are often used in decentralized oracle networks to enable nodes reach consensus on answers to data requests.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] An early idea for this was SchellingCoin (opens in a new tab), a proposed data feed where participants submit responses to "scalar" questions (questions whose answers are described by magnitude, e.g., "what is the price of ETH?"), along with a deposit.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Users who provide values between the 25th and 75th percentile (opens in a new tab) are rewarded, while those whose values deviate largely from the median value are penalized.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] While SchellingCoin doesn’t exist today, a number of decentralized oracles—notably Maker Protocol’s Oracles (opens in a new tab)—use the schelling-point mechanism to improve accuracy of oracle data.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Each Maker Oracle consists of an offchain P2P network of nodes ("relayers" and "feeds") who submit market prices for collateral assets and an onchain “Medianizer” contract that calculates the median of all provided values.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Once the specified delay period is over, this median value becomes the new reference price for the associated asset.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Other examples of oracles that use Schelling point mechanisms include Chainlink Offchain Reporting (opens in a new tab) and Witnet (opens in a new tab).
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] In both systems, responses from oracle nodes in the peer-to-peer network are aggregated into a single aggregate value, such as a mean or median.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Nodes are rewarded or punished according to the extent to which their responses align with or deviate from the aggregate value.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Schelling point mechanisms are attractive because they minimize onchain footprint (only one transaction needs to be sent) while guaranteeing decentralization.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] The latter is possible because nodes must sign off on the list of submitted responses before it is fed into the algorithm that produces the mean/median value.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Decentralized oracle services ensure high availability of offchain data to smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This is achieved by decentralizing both the source of offchain information and nodes responsible for transferring the information onchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This ensures fault-tolerance since the oracle contract can rely on multiple nodes (who also rely on multiple data sources) to execute queries from other contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Decentralization at the source *and* node-operator level is crucial—a network of oracle nodes serving information retrieved from the same source will run into the same problem as a centralized oracle.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] It is also possible for stake-based oracles to slash node operators who fail to respond quickly to data requests.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This significantly incentivizes oracle nodes to invest in fault-tolerant infrastructure and provide data in timely fashion.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Decentralized oracles implement various incentive designs to prevent Byzantine (opens in a new tab) behavior among oracle nodes.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Decentralized oracles—as explained earlier—may require nodes to place a stake on their confidence in the truth of data they submit.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] If the claim checks out, this stake can be returned along with rewards for honest service.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] But it can also be slashed in case the information is incorrect, which provides some measure of accountability.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Decentralized finance (DeFi) applications allow for peer-to-peer lending, borrowing, and trading of assets.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This often requires getting different financial information, including exchange rate data (for calculating the fiat value of cryptocurrencies or comparing token prices) and capital markets data (for calculating the value of tokenized assets, such as gold or the US dollar).
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] A DeFi lending protocol, for example, needs to query current market prices for assets (e.g., ETH) deposited as collateral.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This lets the contract determine the value of collateral assets and determine how much it can borrow from the system.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Popular “price oracles” (as they are often called) in DeFi include Chainlink Price Feeds, Compound Protocol’s Open Price Feed (opens in a new tab), Uniswap’s Time-Weighted Average Prices (TWAPs) (opens in a new tab), and Maker Oracles (opens in a new tab).
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Builders should understand the caveats that come with these price oracles before integrating them into their project.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] This article (opens in a new tab) provides a detailed analysis of what to consider when planning to use any of the price oracles mentioned.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Certain blockchain applications, such as blockchain-based games or lottery schemes, require a high level of unpredictability and randomness to work effectively.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] However, the deterministic execution of blockchains eliminates randomness.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] The original approach was to use pseudorandom cryptographic functions, such as `blockhash`, but these could be manipulated by miners (opens in a new tab) solving the proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Also, Ethereum’s switch to proof-of-stake means developers can no longer rely on `blockhash` for onchain randomness.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] The Beacon Chain’s RANDAO mechanism (opens in a new tab) provides an alternative source of randomness instead.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] It is possible to generate the random value offchain and send it onchain, but doing so imposes high trust requirements on users.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] They must believe the value was truly generated via unpredictable mechanisms and wasn’t altered in transit.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Oracles designed for offchain computation solve this problem by securely generating random outcomes offchain that they broadcast onchain along with cryptographic proofs attesting to the unpredictability of the process.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] An example is Chainlink VRF (opens in a new tab) (Verifiable Random Function), which is a provably fair and tamper-proof random number generator (RNG) useful for building reliable smart contracts for applications that rely on unpredictable outcomes.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] With oracles, creating smart contracts that respond to real-world events is easy.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Oracle services make this possible by allowing contracts to connect to external APIs through offchain components and consume information from those data sources.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] For example, the prediction dapp mentioned earlier may request an oracle to return election results from a trusted offchain source (e.g., the Associated Press).
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Using oracles to retrieve data based on real-world outcomes enables other novel use cases; for example, a decentralized insurance product needs accurate information about weather, disasters, etc. to work effectively.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Smart contracts do not run automatically; rather, an externally owned account (EOA), or another contract account, must trigger the right functions to execute the contract’s code.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] In most cases, the bulk of the contract’s functions are public and can be invoked by EOAs and other contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] But there are also *private functions* within a contract that are inaccessible to others;, but that are critical to a dapp's overall functionality.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Examples include a `mintERC721Token()` function that periodically mints new NFTs for users, a function for awarding payouts in a prediction market, or a function for unlocking staked tokens in a DEX.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Developers will need to trigger such functions at intervals to keep the application running smoothly.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] However, this might lead to more hours lost on mundane tasks for developers, which is why automating execution of smart contracts is attractive.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Some decentralized oracle networks offer automation services, which allow offchain oracle nodes to trigger smart contract functions according to parameters defined by the user.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Typically, this requires “registering” the target contract with the oracle service, providing funds to pay the oracle operator, and specifying the conditions or times to trigger the contract.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Chainlink’s Keeper Network (opens in a new tab) provides options for smart contracts to outsource regular maintenance tasks in a trust minimized and decentralized manner.
[src:blockchain-oracles/developers-oracles] Read the official Keeper's documentation (opens in a new tab) for information on making your contract Keeper-compatible and using the Upkeep service.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In 2014, development work began and was crowdfunded, and the network went live on 30 July 2015.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ethereum allows anyone to deploy decentralized applications onto it, which anyone can then use.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) applications provide financial instruments that do not directly rely on financial intermediaries like brokerages, exchanges, or banks.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] This facilitates borrowing against cryptocurrency holdings or lending them out for interest.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] ERC-20) and non-fungible tokens (NFTs) with a variety of properties, and to create smart contracts that can receive, hold and send those assets in accordance with the contract's immutable code and a transaction's input data.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] On 15 September 2022, Ethereum transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an update known as "The Merge", which cut the blockchain's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ethereum was initially described in late 2013 in a white paper by Vitalik Buterin, a programmer and co-founder of *Bitcoin Magazine*, that described a way to build decentralized applications.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Buterin argued to the Bitcoin Core developers that blockchain technology could benefit from other applications besides money and that it needed a more robust language for application development that could lead to attaching real-world assets, such as stocks and property, to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In 2013, Buterin briefly worked with eToro CEO Yoni Assia on the Colored Coins project and drafted its white paper outlining additional use cases for blockchain technology.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] However, after failing to gain agreement on how the project should proceed, he proposed the development of a new platform with a more robust scripting language—a Turing-complete programming language—that would eventually become Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ethereum was announced at the North American Bitcoin Conference in Miami, in January 2014.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] During the conference, Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, and Anthony Di Iorio (who financed the project) rented a house in Miami with Buterin at which they could develop a fuller sense of what Ethereum might become.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Di Iorio invited friend Joseph Lubin, who invited reporter Morgen Peck, to bear witness.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Peck subsequently wrote about the experience in *Wired*.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Six months later the founders met again in Zug, Switzerland, where Buterin told the founders that the project would proceed as a non-profit.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Hoskinson left the project at that time and soon after founded IOHK, a blockchain company responsible for Cardano.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ethereum has an unusually long list of founders.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Anthony Di Iorio wrote: "Ethereum was founded by Vitalik Buterin, Myself, Charles Hoskinson, Mihai Alisie & Amir Chetrit (the initial 5) in December 2013.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Joseph Lubin, Gavin Wood, & Jeffrey Wilcke were added in early 2014 as founders." Buterin chose the name Ethereum after browsing a list of elements from science fiction on Wikipedia.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Formal development of the software underlying Ethereum began in early 2014 through a Swiss company, Ethereum Switzerland GmbH (*EthSuisse*).The idea of putting executable smart contracts in the blockchain needed to be specified before it could be implemented in software.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] This work was done by Gavin Wood, then the chief technology officer, in the Ethereum Yellow Paper that specified the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Subsequently, a Swiss non-profit foundation, the **Ethereum Foundation** (*Stiftung Ethereum*), was founded.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Development was funded by an online public crowd sale from July to August 2014, in which participants bought the Ethereum value token (ether) with another digital currency, bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] While there was early praise for the technical innovations of Ethereum, questions were also raised about its security and scalability.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The intended purpose of the three distinct implementations would be so that if one of them had a bug, the other two could be used as a comparison.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Several codenamed prototypes of Ethereum were developed over 18 months in 2014 and 2015 by the Ethereum Foundation as part of their proof-of-concept series.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] "Olympic" was the last prototype and public beta pre-release.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The Olympic network gave users a bug bounty of 25,000 ether for stress-testing the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] On 30 July 2015, "Frontier" marked the official launch of the Ethereum platform, and Ethereum created its "genesis block".
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The genesis block contained 8,893 transactions allocating various amounts of ether to different addresses, and a block reward of 5 ETH.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Since the initial launch, Ethereum has undergone a number of planned protocol upgrades, which are important changes affecting the underlying functionality and/or incentive structures of the platform.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Protocol upgrades are accomplished by means of a hard fork.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In 2016, a decentralized autonomous organization called The DAO—a set of smart contracts developed on the platform—raised a record US$150 million in a crowd sale to fund the project.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Emin Gün Sirer, Vlad Zamfir and Dino Mark had written a paper called *A Call for a Temporary Moratorium on The DAO* in which they described in which way the DAO might be vunerable to attacks.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The DAO was exploited in June 2016 when US$50 million of DAO tokens were stolen by an unknown hacker.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The event sparked a debate in the crypto-community about whether Ethereum should perform a contentious "hard fork" to reappropriate the affected funds.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The fork resulted in the network splitting into two blockchains: Ethereum with the theft reversed, and Ethereum Classic which continued on the original chain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In March 2017, various blockchain startups, research groups, and *Fortune* 500 companies announced the creation of the Enterprise Ethereum Alliance (EEA) with 30 founding members.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] By May 2017, the nonprofit organization had 116 enterprise members, including ConsenSys, CME Group, Cornell University's research group, Toyota Research Institute, Samsung SDS, Microsoft, Intel, J.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Morgan, Cooley LLP, Merck KGaA, DTCC, Deloitte, Accenture, Banco Santander, BNY Mellon, ING, and National Bank of Canada.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] By July 2017, there were over 150 members in the alliance, including MasterCard, Cisco Systems, Sberbank, and Scotiabank.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In 2024, Paul Brody, EEA board member for EY, was announced as the new chairperson, and Karen Scarbrough, board member for Microsoft, as the new executive director.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Vanessa Grellet from Arche Capital also joined as a new board member.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In 2017, *CryptoKitties*, the blockchain game and decentralized application (dApp) featuring digital cat artwork as NFTs, was launched on the Ethereum network.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In cultivating popularity with users and collectors, it gained notable mainstream media attention providing significant exposure to Ethereum in the process.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] It was considered the most popular smart contract in use on the network but it also highlighted concerns over Ethereum's scalability due to the game's substantial consumption of network capacity at the time.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In January 2018, a community-driven paper (an EIP, "Ethereum Improvement Proposal") under the leadership of civic hacker and lead author William Entriken was published, called *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard.* It introduced ERC-721, the first official NFT standard on Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] This standardization allowed Ethereum to become central to a multi-billion dollar digital collectibles market.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] By January 2018, ether was the second-largest cryptocurrency in terms of market capitalization, behind bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] As of 2021, it maintained that relative position.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In 2019, Ethereum Foundation employee Virgil Griffith was arrested by the US government for presenting at a blockchain conference in North Korea.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] He would later plead guilty to one count of conspiring to violate the International Emergency Economic Powers Act in 2021.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In March 2021, Visa Inc. announced that it began settling stablecoin transactions using Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In April 2021, JP Morgan Chase, UBS, and MasterCard announced that they were investing US$65 million into ConsenSys, a software development firm that builds Ethereum-related infrastructure.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] There were two network upgrades in 2021.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The first was "Berlin", implemented on 14 April 2021.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The second was "London", which took effect on 5 August.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The London upgrade included Ethereum Improvement Proposal ("EIP") 1559, a mechanism for reducing transaction fee volatility.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The mechanism causes a portion of the ether paid in transaction fees for each block to be destroyed rather than given to the block proposer, reducing the inflation rate of ether and potentially resulting in periods of deflation.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] On 27 August 2021, the blockchain experienced a brief fork that was the result of clients running different incompatible software versions.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] "The Merge" (formerly called Ethereum 2.0) was a set of three updates (Bellatrix, Paris, and Shapella) that transitioned Ethereum's consensus protocol from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Bellatrix updated the proof-of-stake Beacon chain and introduced economic slashing.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Paris was the event at block 15537393 on 15 September 2022 that merged Ethereum to the Beacon chain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Shapella (Shanghai-Capella) was the update that allowed for staking withdrawals.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The switch from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake has cut Ethereum's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] However, the effect this has on global energy consumption and climate change may be limited since the computers previously used for mining ether may be used to mine other cryptocurrencies that are energy-intensive.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] On 13 March 2024, "Dencun" or also "Deneb-Cancun" set of upgrades went live.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] These included EIP-4844 (Proto-Danksharding) which introduced "blobs" that can be used for general-purpose data-availability.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Because "Blob" data is stored only temporarily, it is much cheaper than using normal call data for storage.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] This allows for Ethereum Layer 2 (L2) networks to greatly reduce the cost of posting compressed transaction data to the Layer 1 (L1).
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The Prague-Electra ("Pectra") update was launched on 7 May 2025.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The Fulu-Osaka update went live on 3 December 2025.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] This update introduced several protocol improvements.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ethereum is a peer-to-peer network that maintains a database containing the storage values of all Ethereum accounts and processes state-altering transactions.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Approximately every 12 seconds, a batch of new transactions, known as a "block", is processed by the network.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Each block contains a cryptographic hash identifying the series of blocks that must precede it if the block is to be considered valid.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] This series of blocks is known as the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Each "node" (network participant) connects with a relatively small subset of the network to offer blocks and unvalidated transactions (i.e. transactions not yet in the blockchain) to its peers for download, and it downloads any from its peers that it doesn't already have.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Each node usually has a unique set of peers, so that offering an item to its peers results in the propagation of that item throughout the entire network within seconds.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] A node's collection of unvalidated transactions is known as its "mempool".
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] A node may choose to create a copy of the state for itself.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] It does this by starting with the genesis state and executing every transaction in the blockchain, in the proper order of blocks and in the order they are listed within each block.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may "stake" (deposit) 32 or more ETH to register a "validator".
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] At the end of each "epoch" (32 block slots, each slot lasting 12 seconds), each validator is pseudorandomly assigned to one of the slots of the epoch after the next, either as the block proposer or as an attester.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] During a slot, the block proposer uses their mempool to create a block that is intended to become the new "head" (latest block) of the blockchain, and the attesters attest to which block is at the head of the chain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] If a validator makes self-contradicting proposals or attestations, or if it is inactive, it loses a portion of its stake.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may send ETH to a validator at any time to increase its stake.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] A validator's attestation is given a weight equal to its stake or 2,048, whichever is less.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] According to the Ethereum protocol, the blockchain with the highest accumulated weight of attestations at any given time is to be regarded as the canonical chain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Validators are rewarded for making valid proposals and attestations.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] A validator's rewards are paid via transactions within the same chain that contains their proposal or attestation, and therefore would have little or no market value unless that chain becomes the canonical chain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] This incentivizes validators to support the chain that they think other validators view as the canonical chain, which results in a high degree of consensus.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ether (ETH) is the cryptocurrency generated in accordance with the Ethereum protocol as a reward to validators in a proof-of-stake system for adding blocks to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ether is represented in the state as an unsigned integer associated with each account, this being the account's ETH balance denominated in wei (1018 wei = 1 ether).
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] At the end of each epoch, new ETH is generated by the addition of protocol-specified amounts to the balances of all validators that made valid block proposals or attestations in the epoch before the last (i.e. the epoch being finalized).
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Additionally, ether is the only currency accepted by the protocol as payment for the transaction fee.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The transaction fee is composed of two parts: the base fee and the tip.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The base fee is "burned" (deleted from existence) and the tip goes to the block proposer.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The validator reward together with the tips provide the incentive to validators to keep the blockchain growing (i.e. to keep processing new transactions).
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Therefore, ETH is fundamental to the operation of the network.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ether may be "sent" from one account to another via a transaction, the execution of which simply entails subtracting the *amount to be sent* from the sender's balance and adding the same amount to the recipient's balance.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ether is often erroneously referred to as "Ethereum".
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The uppercase Greek letter Xi, Ξ, is sometimes used as a currency symbol for ether.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] There are two types of accounts on Ethereum: user accounts (also known as externally-owned accounts), and contract accounts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Both types have an ETH balance, may transfer ETH to any account, may execute the code of another contract, or create a new contract, and are identified on the blockchain and in the state by an account address.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Contracts are the only type of account that has associated bytecode and storage (to store contract-specific state).
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The code of a contract is evaluated when a transaction is sent to it.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The code of the contract may read user-specified data from the transaction, and may have a return value.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ethereum account addresses are composed of the prefix "`0x`" (a common identifier for hexadecimal) concatenated with the rightmost 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the ECDSA public key (the curve used is the so-called *secp256k1*).
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In hexadecimal, two digits represent a byte, and so addresses contain 40 hexadecimal digits after the "`0x`", e.g.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Contract addresses are in the same format, however, they are determined by sender and creation transaction nonce.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) is the runtime environment for transaction execution in Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The EVM is a stack based virtual machine with an instruction set specifically designed for Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The instruction set includes, among other things, stack operations, memory operations, and operations to inspect the current execution context, such as remaining gas, information about the current block, and the current transaction.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The EVM is designed to be deterministic on a wide variety of hardware and operating systems, so that given a pre-transaction state and a transaction, each node produces the same post-transaction state, thereby enabling network consensus.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The formal definition of the EVM is specified in the Ethereum Yellow Paper.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] EVMs have been implemented in C++, C#, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Python, Ruby, Rust, Elixir, Erlang, and soon WebAssembly.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Gas is a unit of account within the EVM used in the calculation of the transaction fee, which is the amount of ETH a transaction's sender must pay to the network to have the transaction included in the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Each type of operation which may be performed by the EVM is hardcoded with a certain gas cost, which is intended to be roughly proportional to the monetary value of the resources (e.g. computation and storage) a node must expend or dedicate to perform that operation.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] When a sender is creating a transaction, the sender must specify a *gas limit* and *gas price*.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The *gas limit* is the maximum amount of gas the sender is willing to use in the transaction, and the *gas price* is the amount of ETH the sender wishes to pay to the network per unit of gas used.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] A transaction may only be included in the blockchain at a block slot that has a *base gas price* less than or equal to the transaction's *gas price*.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The portion of the *gas price* that is in excess of the *base gas price* is known as the tip and goes to the block proposer; the higher the tip, the more incentive a block proposer has to include the transaction in their block, and thus the quicker the transaction will be included in the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The sender buys the full amount of gas (i.e. their ETH balance is debited *gas limit* × *gas price* and their gas balance is set to *gas limit*) up-front, at the start of the execution of the transaction, and is refunded at the end for any unused gas.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] If at any point the transaction does not have enough gas to perform the next operation, the transaction is reverted but the sender is still only refunded for the unused gas.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In user interfaces, gas prices are typically denominated in gigawei (Gwei), a subunit of ETH equal to 10−9 ETH.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The EVM's instruction set is Turing-complete.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ethereum's smart contracts are written in high-level programming languages and then compiled down to EVM bytecode, which is then deployed to the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] They can be written in Solidity (a language library with similarities to C and JavaScript), as well as others.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Source code and compiler information are usually published on blockchain explorer websites soon after the launch of the contract so that users can see the code and verify that it compiles to the bytecode that is on-chain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] One issue related to using smart contracts on a public blockchain is that bugs, including security holes, are visible to all but cannot be fixed quickly.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] One example of this is the 2016 attack on The DAO, which could not be quickly stopped or reversed.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The ERC-20 (Ethereum Request-for-Comments #20) Token Standard allows for fungible tokens on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The standard, proposed by Fabian Vogelsteller in November 2015, implements an API for tokens within smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The standard provides functions that include the transfer of tokens from one account to another, getting the current token balance of an account, and getting the total supply of the token available on the network.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Smart contracts that correctly implement ERC-20 processes are called ERC-20 Token Contracts, and they keep track of created tokens on Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Numerous cryptocurrencies have launched as ERC-20 tokens and have been distributed through initial coin offerings.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ethereum also allows for the creation of unique and indivisible tokens, called non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Since tokens of this type are unique, they have been used to represent such things as collectibles, digital art, sports memorabilia, virtual real estate, and items within games.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] ERC-721 is the first official NFT standard for Ethereum and was followed up by ERC-1155 which introduced semi-fungibility; both are widely used, though some fully fungible tokens using ERC-20 have been used for NFTs such as *CryptoPunks*.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The first NFT project, Etheria, a 3D map of tradable and customizable hexagonal tiles, was deployed to the network in October 2015 and demonstrated live at DEVCON1 in November of that year.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In 2021, Christie's sold a digital image with an NFT by Beeple for US$69.3 million, making him the third-most-valuable living artist in terms of auction prices at the time, although observers have noted that both the buyer and seller had a vested interest in driving demand for the artist's work.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) offers financial instruments in a decentralized architecture, outside of companies' and governments' control, such as money market funds which let users earn interest.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] DeFi applications are typically accessed through a Web3-enabled browser extension or application, such as MetaMask, which allows users to directly interact with the Ethereum blockchain through a website.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Many of these DApps can connect and work together to create complex financial services.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Examples of DeFi platforms include MakerDAO.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Uniswap, a decentralized exchange for tokens on Ethereum grew from US$20 million in liquidity to US$2.9 billion in 2020.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] As of October 2020, over US$11 billion was invested in various DeFi protocols.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Additionally, through a process called "wrapping", certain DeFi protocols allow synthetic versions of various assets (such as bitcoin, gold, and oil) to be tradeable on Ethereum and also compatible with all of Ethereum's major wallets and applications.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Aave is a protocol for microlending using Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ethereum-based software and networks, independent from the public Ethereum chain, have been tested by enterprise software companies.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Interested parties have included Microsoft, IBM, JPMorgan Chase, Deloitte, R3, and Innovate UK (cross-border payments prototype).
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Barclays, UBS, Credit Suisse, Amazon, Visa, and other companies have also experimented with Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] As of December 2025, the maximum theoretical throughput for Ethereum L1 is 238 TPS (given its current 60M gas limit, 12s blocks, and 21k gas cost for ETH transfers).
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Due to large smart contract and batch transaction using more gas in each block, the average transaction throughput is much less.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] As of January 2016, the Ethereum averaged about 25 transactions per second; this did not change after the move to proof-of-stake.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In comparison, the Visa payment platform processes 45,000 payments per second.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] This has led some to question the scalability of Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Ethereum's blockchain uses a Merkle–Patricia Tree to store account state in each block.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The trie allows for storage savings, set membership proofs (called "Merkle proofs"), and light client synchronization.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The network has faced congestion problems, such as in 2017 in relation to *CryptoKitties*.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Layer 2 (L2) is one of the approaches that the Ethereum ecosystem has developed in order to scale up and handle more transactions with lower transaction fees.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] A Layer 2 chain is a separate blockchain that extends Ethereum (Layer 1) and inherits the security guarantees of Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] There are different types of L2 chains, including optimistic rollups and zero-knowledge rollups (zk rollups).
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Depending on their individual technical details, some L2 chains are capable of processing thousands of transactions per second.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The legal status of ether (ETH), Ethereum's native token, remains subject to uncertainty and varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In the United States, regulatory authorities have increasingly signaled that ether should be treated as a commodity under the jurisdiction of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC).
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] The CFTC has repeatedly asserted its regulatory authority over Ethereum, with former CFTC Chairman Heath Tarbert stating in 2019 that "ETH is a commodity" and subsequent leadership maintaining this position.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] From a private law perspective, many jurisdictions have recognized ether as a form of intangible personal property that can be owned, transferred, and used as collateral, similar to other forms of personal property.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] In the United States specifically, the 2022 Amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property that includes digital assets like ether.
[src:blockchain-oracles/ethereum] Under UCC Article 12, ETH is classified as a CER, which provides a comprehensive framework for its commercial circulation.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] A **smart contract** is a computer program or a transaction protocol that is intended to automatically execute, control or document events and actions according to the terms of a contract or an agreement.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] The objectives of smart contracts are the reduction of need for trusted intermediators, arbitration costs, and fraud losses, as well as the reduction of malicious and accidental exceptions.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Smart contracts are commonly associated with cryptocurrencies, and the smart contracts introduced by Ethereum are generally considered a fundamental building block for decentralized finance (DeFi) and non-fungible token (NFT) applications.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] The original Ethereum white paper by Vitalik Buterin in 2014 describes the Bitcoin protocol as a weak version of the smart contract concept as originally defined by Nick Szabo, and proposed a stronger version based on the Solidity language, which is Turing complete.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Since then, various cryptocurrencies have supported programming languages which allow for more advanced smart contracts between untrusted parties.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] A smart contract should not be confused with a smart legal contract, which is a traditional, natural-language, legally binding agreement that has selected terms expressed and implemented in machine-readable code.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] By 1996, Nick Szabo was using the term "smart contract" to refer to contracts which would be enforced by physical property (such as hardware or software) instead of by law.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Szabo described vending machines as an example of this concept.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] In 1998, the term was used to describe objects in rights management service layer of the system *The Stanford Infobus*, which was a part of Stanford Digital Library Project.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] A *smart contract* does not typically constitute a valid binding agreement at law.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Proposals exist to regulate smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Smart contracts are not legal agreements, but instead transactions which are executed automatically by a computer program or a transaction protocol, such as technological means for the automation of payment obligations such as by transferring cryptocurrencies or other tokens.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Some scholars have argued that the imperative or declarative nature of programming languages would impact the legal validity of smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] In some jurisdictions, legal scholars have examined how the rigidity of smart contracts interacts with traditional doctrines such as contractual unforeseeability.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Since the 2015 launch of the Ethereum blockchain, the term "smart contract" has been applied to general purpose computation that takes place on a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] The US National Institute of Standards and Technology describes a "smart contract" as a "collection of code and data (sometimes referred to as functions and state) that is deployed using cryptographically signed transactions on the blockchain network".
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] In this interpretation a smart contract is any kind of computer program which uses a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] A smart contract also can be regarded as a secured stored procedure, as its execution and codified effects (like the transfer of tokens between parties) cannot be manipulated without modifying the blockchain itself.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] In this interpretation, the execution of contracts is controlled and audited by the platform, not by arbitrary server-side programs connecting to the platform.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] In 2018, a US Senate report said: "While smart contracts might sound new, the concept is rooted in basic contract law.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Usually, the judicial system adjudicates contractual disputes and enforces terms, but it is also common to have another arbitration method, especially for international transactions.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] With smart contracts, a program enforces the contract built into the code." States in the US which have passed legislation on the use of smart contracts include Arizona, Iowa, Nevada, Tennessee, and Wyoming.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] In April 2021, the UK Jurisdiction Taskforce (UKJT) published the Digital Dispute Resolution Rules (the Digital DR Rules), which were intended to enable the rapid resolution of blockchain and crypto legal disputes in Britain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Similar to a transfer of value on a blockchain, deployment of a smart contract on a blockchain occurs by sending a transaction from a wallet for the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] The transaction includes the compiled code for the smart contract as well as a special receiver address.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] That transaction must then be included in a block that is added to the blockchain, at which point the smart contract's code will execute to establish the initial state of the smart contract.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Byzantine fault-tolerant algorithms secure the smart contract in a decentralized way from attempts to tamper with it.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Once a smart contract is deployed, it cannot be updated.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Smart contracts on a blockchain can store arbitrary state and execute arbitrary computations.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] End clients interact with a smart contract through transactions.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Such transactions with a smart contract can invoke other smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] These transactions might result in changing the state and sending coins from one smart contract to another or from one account to another.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] The most popular blockchain for running smart contracts is Ethereum.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] On Ethereum, smart contracts are typically written in a Turing-complete programming language called Solidity, and compiled into low-level bytecode to be executed by the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Due to the halting problem and other security problems, Turing-completeness is considered to be a risk and is deliberately avoided by languages like Vyper.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Some of the other smart contract programming languages missing Turing-completeness are Simplicity, Scilla, Ivy and Bitcoin Script.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Some newer platforms have explored "asset-oriented" domain-specific languages (such as Scrypto) that treat digital assets as native data types within the language environment to enforce finiteness and safety rules at the compiler level.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] However, measurements in 2020 using regular expressions showed that only 35.3% of 53,757 Ethereum smart contracts at that time included recursions and loops — constructs connected to the halting problem.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Several languages are designed to enable formal verification: Bamboo, IELE, Simplicity, Michelson (can be verified with Rocq), Liquidity (compiles to Michelson), Scilla, DAML and Pact.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Processes on a blockchain are generally deterministic in order to ensure Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Nevertheless, real world application of smart contracts, such as lotteries and casinos, require secure randomness.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] In fact, blockchain technology reduces the costs for conducting of a lottery and is therefore beneficial for the participants.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Randomness on blockchain can be implemented by using block hashes or timestamps, oracles, commitment schemes, special smart contracts like RANDAO and Quanta, as well as sequences from mixed strategy Nash equilibria.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] In 1998, Szabo proposed that smart contract infrastructure can be implemented by replicated asset registries and contract execution using cryptographic hash chains and Byzantine fault-tolerant replication.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Askemos implemented this approach in 2002 using Scheme (later adding SQLite) as the contract script language.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] One proposal for using Bitcoin for replicated asset registration and contract execution is called "colored coins".
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Replicated titles for potentially arbitrary forms of property, along with replicated contract execution, are implemented in different projects.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] As of 2015, UBS was experimenting with "smart bonds" that use the bitcoin blockchain in which payment streams could hypothetically be fully automated, creating a self-paying instrument.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Inheritance wishes could hypothetically be implemented automatically upon registration of a death certificate by means of smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Birth certificates can also work together with smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Chris Snook of *Inc.com* suggests smart contracts could also be used to handle real estate transactions and could be used in the field of title records and in the public register.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Seth Oranburg and Liya Palagashvili argue that smart contracts could also be used in employment contracts, especially temporary employment contracts, which according to them would benefit the employer.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] The transactions data from a blockchain-based smart contract is visible to all users in the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] The data provides cryptographic view of the transactions, however, this leads to a situation where bugs, including security holes, are visible to all yet may not be quickly fixed.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Such an attack, difficult to fix quickly, was successfully executed on The DAO in June 2016, draining approximately US$50 million worth of Ether at the time, while developers attempted to come to a solution that would gain consensus.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] The DAO program had a time delay in place before the hacker could remove the funds; a hard fork of the Ethereum software was done to claw back the funds from the attacker before the time limit expired.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Other high-profile attacks include the Parity multisignature wallet attacks, and an integer underflow/overflow attack (2018), totaling over US$184 million.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Smart legal contracts are distinct from smart contracts.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] As mentioned above, a smart contract is not necessarily legally enforceable as a contract.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] On the other hand, a smart legal contract has all the elements of a legally enforceable contract in the jurisdiction in which it can be enforced and it can be enforced by a court or tribunal.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] Therefore, while every smart legal contract will contain some elements of a smart contract, not every smart contract will be a smart legal contract.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] There is no formal definition of a smart legal contract in the legal industry.
[src:blockchain-oracles/smart-contract] A Ricardian contract is a type of smart legal contract.
